tacit knowledge, uses of truth and reification. Drawing upon genealogical theory and accounts of slavery as social death, the fourth dimension of power concerns the power to create social subjects. The book concludes with an original normative pragmatist power-based account of democracy.Offering lucid and entertaining illustrations of complex theoretical perspectives, this book is essential reading for undergraduates, postgraduates and academics, while offering an indispensable guide for activists wishing to understand domination, resistance and empowerment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aPower (Social sciences)xPolitical aspects. 0aPower (Social sciences)xPsychological aspects. 0aPower (Social sciences). 4aPolitical Studies 2020. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aMichel Foucault.  aSteven Lukes.  aconflict.  ademocracy.  adomination.  aempowerment.  aideology.  apolitical power.  areification.  asocial structure.1 aHaugaard, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611038140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526110381423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526110381/original  a978-3-11-128248-0  Manchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packageb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles